07510nam a22009255i 9783110764734DE-B159720230502090707.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230502t20212022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107647347 a10.1515/97831107647342doi  a(DE-B1597)596892  a(OCoLC)1291506853  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aHIS0020102bisacsh00aMateriality in Roman Art and Architecture :bAesthetics, Semantics and Function /ced. by Annette Haug, Adrian Hielscher, M. Taylor Lauritsen. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (VIII, 286 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDecorative Principles in Late Republican and Early Imperial Italy (Decor) ,x2702-4989 ;v300tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tMateriality as Decor: Aesthetics, Semantics and Function -- tSurface Matters: 'True' and 'False' Gloss in Architecture -- tEthical Matters: Pliny the Elder on Material Deception -- tMateriality of Architecture: Aesthetics -- tThe Humble Material: Masonry and Meaning in Roman Architecture -- tMarble Wall Revetment in Central Italy during the First Century A.D.: Aesthetics and Decorative Effects -- tUse, Aesthetics and Semantics of Coloured Marble Columns in the Western Mediterranean during the Late Republic and Early Roman Empire -- tHard as Rock and Light as Air: Stucco Ceilings in Roman Domestic Space -- tDiverging Trends in the Visual Appearance of Fired Clay in Roman Architecture: 'Campana Plaques' and Terracotta Façades -- tMateriality of Architecture: Semantics -- tThe Meaning of Building Materials in Late Republican Architecture: Moving from Semantics to Pragmatics -- tTravertine in Rome: Its Style and Meaning -- tMateriality of Objects -- tFour-Legged Marble Tables (mensae) in Pompeian Houses: The Intersection of Function, Aesthetics and Semantics -- tMateriality and Object Design and Function: Perspectives from Artefacts -- tNon Arte, Sed Naturae? Remarks on Roman Cameos and their Visual Effects -- tRoman Basket Urns as Elements in a Transmaterial Design System -- tAn Age of Intermateriality: Skeuomorphism and Intermateriality Between the Late Republic and Early Empire -- tAuthor Biographies0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe focus of this volume is on the aesthetics, semantics and function of materials in Roman antiquity between the 2nd century B.C. and the 2nd century A.D. It includes contributions on both architectural spaces (and their material design) and objects - types of 'artefacts' that differ greatly in the way they were used, perceived and loaded with cultural significance. With respect to architecture, the analysis of material aesthetics leads to a new understanding of the performance, imitation and transformation of surfaces, including the social meaning of such strategies. In the case of objects, surface treatments are equally important. However, object form (a specific design category), which can enter into tension with materiality, comes into particular focus. Only when materials are shaped do their various qualities emerge, and these qualities are, to a greater or lesser extent, transferred to objects. With a focus primarily on Roman Italy, the papers in this volume underscore the importance of material design and highlight the awareness of this matter in the ancient world.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 4aDekor. 4aMaterialität. 4aObjektdesign. 4aRömisches Architektur. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Greece.2bisacsh  aMateriality.  aRoman architecture.  